'''Kushiyatama''' (櫛八玉神), also known as Kiyahatama no Kami, is a deity appearing in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==
Kushiyatama appears in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft}} during the episode of the {{ill|Transfer of the Land|ja|国譲り|12=draft}}. He is considered the ancestor of the Bekke clan.

== Depiction ==
=== In the Kojiki ===
After {{ill|Takeminakata|ja|建御名方神|12=draft}} surrenders to {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|建御雷神|12=draft}}, Takemikazuchi asks {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主神|12=draft}} about his loyalty. Ōkuninushi agrees to submit the land of Ashihara-no-Nakatsukuni if a grand palace is built for him, akin to the residence of the heavenly gods.

During the construction of the heavenly palace in Tagi no Kohama (present-day {{ill|Izumo|ja|出雲市|12=draft}}), Kushiyatama, the grandson of the water deities Hayakitsuhiko and Hayakitsuhime, is appointed as the imperial chef. He transforms into a cormorant, gathers clay from the sea floor to create sacred vessels, and produces fire to prepare divine offerings. This act symbolizes his role as the ancestral deity of cuisine.

== Enshrined Shrines ==
* Mikado-nushi-hiko Shrine ({{ill|Nanao|ja|七尾市|12=draft}}, Ishikawa Prefecture)
* Hida Takatsue Shrine ({{ill|Gero|ja|下呂市|12=draft}}, Gifu Prefecture)
